<br>
I've always done my inking with throw away pens. Do you just simply dip these types of pens into ink and then draw till the bit of ink of the nib is gone or is there some trick with these pens? also if you do just redip how long does usally one dip last? I am thinking about going with fixed nib pens that take cartridges but I am sure the price is going to add up far faster than just buying ink? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uplatinumdraco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Platinum Draco</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(7/27/02 10:20:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4057.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How to use ink with non-cartridge fixed nib pen's?</span><hr size=1> oh gods... these thing are freaky...<br>
<br>
ok, from my expirence... the basics are:<br>
<br>
PRECLEAN AND STARTUP<br>
<br>
you select a nib, get some scratch paper and some paper towels... and maybe a cup of water.<br>
<br>
ok, first, dip said nib in ink, then let alot of the ink bleed off back into the well.<br>
<br>
then tap GENTLY, the tip of the nib, even lighter if it's a small one, to get even more ink out, this prevents globs... now, your pen should have a film of ink around it.<br>
<br>
PROPER USE AND HANDLING<br>
<br>
ok, the trick is to use the sides and edges to get the correct widths... note that these are pressure sensitive, the harder you press, the thicker the line, and the faster your ink runs out. i prefer to make thick lines and filled areas with a brush.<br>
<br>
one tip is to avoid a) digging into the paper.<br>
b) going over the same line twice, it's alright to overlap, but avoid it nontheless.<br>
<br>
MID AND ENDCLEAN<br>
<br>
ok, during your inking job, you will note that you pen collects paper fibers, so you dry the ink off and wipe the nib with the paper towels, then redip ink and repeat previous steps.<br>
<br>
now, when you are finished with a nib, throw the nib and holder into the water cup and swish it around a bit, wait, then wipe it off... if you do this after each peice, it will prolong your nibs lifespan.<br>
<br>
Enjoy. <p>In the heavens, far, far above our beloved and behated characters, doom
